  "notes": "Middle Persian / Pahlavi (~224–900 CE). Language of the Sasanian Empire (224–651 CE) and Zoroastrian religious texts. KEY INNOVATIONS vs. Old Persian: (1) Intervocalic consonant LENITION: p→w/b, t→d (θ→d), k→g→γ; (2) Diphthong MONOPHTHONGISATION: *ai → ē [eː], *au → ō [oː]; (3) 6-quality vowel system: a, ā, ē, ī, ō, ū; (4) xw- cluster preserved as /xʷ/ (later → x in New Persian). Script: Pahlavi (Aramaeographic; Aramaic logograms 'huzvarishn'). Arabic conquest (651 CE): Arabic becomes administrative language; Arabic loanwords begin entering. ISO 639-2: pal (Pahlavi). References: Mackenzie (1971), Brunner (1977).",
